Xposed is a framework for Android devices that lets users modify apps and system behavior without changing the original files. While it allows customization, it can also be risky because malicious modules might access sensitive data or bypass security. If a device uses Xposed, attackers can exploit it to weaken protections, making private data vulnerable. Understanding “root access,” “module injection,” and “system modification” can help explore how such tools affect security. Using secure, unmodified devices reduces risks and better protects encrypted communications and sensitive information.